{"id":"1805.04038","submitter":"Babak Samadi","authors":"Doost Ali Mojdeh, Babak Samadi and Ismael G. Yero","title":"Packing and domination parameters in digraphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Discrete Applied Mathematics, 269 (2019), 184-192","doi":"10.1016/j.dam.2019.04.008","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Given a digraph $D=(V,A)$, a set $B\\subset V$ is a packing set in $D$ if\nthere are no arcs joining vertices of $B$ and for any two vertices $x,y\\in B$\nthe sets of in-neighbors of $x$ and $y$ are disjoint. The set $S$ is a\ndominating set (an open dominating set) in $D$ if every vertex not in $S$ (in\n$V$) has an in-neighbor in $S$. Moreover, a dominating set $S$ is called a\ntotal dominating set if the subgraph induced by $S$ has no isolated vertices.\nThe packing sets of maximum cardinality and the (total, open) dominating sets\nof minimum cardinality in digraphs are studied in this article. We prove that\nthe two optimal sets concerning packing and domination achieve the same value\nfor directed trees, and give some applications of it. We also show analogous\nequalities for all connected contrafunctional digraphs, and characterize all\nsuch digraphs $D$ for which such equalities are satisfied. Moreover, sharp\nbounds on the maximum and the minimum cardinalities of packing and dominating\nsets, respectively, are given for digraphs. Finally, we present solutions for\ntwo open problems, concerning total and open dominating sets of minimum\ncardinality, pointed out in [Australas. J. Combin. 39 (2007), 283--292].\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 May 2018 16:08:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-25"}
