{"id":"1805.04087","submitter":"Ilia Musco","authors":"Cristiano Germani and Ilia Musco","title":"The abundance of primordial black holes depends on the shape of the\n  inflationary power spectrum","comments":"Final version: Strongly improved with additional discussions and new\n  figures, references added, results unchanged. 6 pages and 2 figures. Accepted\n  to be published in Phys. Rev. Letter","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 122, 141302 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.122.141302","report-no":"ICCUB-18-009","categories":"astro-ph.CO gr-qc hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this letter, combining peak theory and the numerical analysis of\ngravitational collapse in the radiation dominated era, we show that the\nabundance of primordial blacks holes, generated by an enhancement in the\ninflationary power spectrum, is extremely dependent on the shape of the peak.\nGiven the amplitude of the power spectrum, we show that the density of\nprimordial black holes generated from a narrow peak, is exponentially smaller\nthan in the case of a broad peak. Specifically, for a top-hat profile of the\npower spectrum in Fourier space, we find that for having primordial black holes\ncomprising all of the dark matter, one would only need a power spectrum\namplitude an order of magnitude smaller than suggested previously whereas in\nthe case of a narrow peak, one would instead need a much larger power spectrum\namplitude, which in many cases would invalidate the perturbative analysis of\ncosmological perturbations. Finally, we show that, although critical collapse\ngives a broad mass spectrum, the density of primordial black holes formed is\ndominated by masses roughly equal to the cosmological horizon mass measured at\nhorizon crossing.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 10 May 2018 17:42:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 May 2018 16:57:00 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 22 Oct 2018 16:31:16 GMT"},{"